defaultIntroductiondefault1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK National Ecosystem Assessment provides a comprehensive 
defaultaccount of how the natural environment and its biodiversity provide us with services that are critical to our wellbeing and economic prosperity
default. 
defaultDespite this, biodiversity 
defaultis being continually eroded and fragmented by inappropriate development
default. T
defaulthe 
defaultplanning system does not adequately guard against biodiversity loss; the mitigation hierarchy is inconsistently applied
default,
default and where compensation does take place it is often inadequate and short-lived. 
default2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAt the same time, there is an acute s
defaultocial need for mor
defaulte housing, alongside
default better infrastructure for business
default. Despite this,
default the planning system is
default often
default slow and cumbersome. It is, therefore, only right that Government explores ways in which to make the planning system more fit for purpose, so that it can de
defaultliver truly sustainable development. 
defaultThe
defaultre is undoubtedly potential
default for 
defaulta new
default system 
defaultthat could take
default a
default systematic account of the value 
defaultof
default nature, 
defaultsave money for business, and
default increase speed in
default a simpler
default planning system
default. 
default3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHowever, the Government’s preferred
default options raise a series of 
defaultsignificant concerns that
default will need to be addressed before a
defaultny new
default system is established.  
defaultIn particular, o
defaultffsetting must only be established as part of a coherent strengthening of the mitigation hierarchy; it must be supported b
defaulty real, independent ecological expertise at a local level; it must be applied uniformly across developments; and it must be underpinned by a long-term financial and legal framework for monitoring, reporting and implementation. If this can be achieved, biod
defaultiv
defaultersity offsetting can deliver
default potential benefits for econo
defaultmy, society and environment. Conversely,
default if 
defaultt
defaulthese issues cannot be addressed, biodiversity offsetting 
defaultrisks serious damage to our natural environment.
defaultThe mdefaultitigation hierarchy default4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultRecreating complex 
defaultnatural processes is inherently difficult and full of risk. Essentially, you are guaranteeing ecological loss in return for uncertain gains.
default Even if the offset is successful, in many cases there will be a temporal loss of biodiversity that can never be ret
defaultrieved.
default As such, in-situ conservation is always preferable. 
default5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThat offsetting biodiversity loss is incredibly difficult is evidenced 
defaultby the fact that there are no systems in the world that have been able to demonstrate no net loss of biodiversity, and t
defaulthe w
defaultealth of studies showing (often considerable) net-
default losses
default. 
defaultIndeed, we would seriously 
defaultquestion the repeated statements in the Impact Assessment
default,
default that offsetting wil
defaultl ‘improve biodiversity’, given the 
defaultabsence of any evidence to support this statement.  
default 
default6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is because of the uncertainty and risk associated with offsetting that the mitigation hierarchy must be adhered to
default, as required by the National Planning Policy Framework (NPPF)
default. O
defaultffse
defaulttting should
default only ever
default be
default undertaken when a development is absolutely 
defaultnecessary, and all attempts to avoid harm or mitigate it have been exhausted. 
defaultWe welcome the statements in the Green Paper that the mitigation hierarchy is adhered to, but this assertion is undermined and contradicted by the explicit desire for offsetting 
defaultto free up more land on site for development (because mitigation will no longer be necessary). This is a blatant
default disregard of
default the mitigation hierarchy
default,
default to which we strongly object.
default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe would consider 
defaultthe failure of LPAs to avoid and mitigate harm from devel
defaultopment to be a far more serious problem for biodiversity than the poor implementation of any necessary compensation. This is largely due to a culture of not va
defaultluing biodiversity and not giving
default due weight to policies concerned with biodiversity – a point su
defaultpported by Defra commissioned research into the implementation of PPS9
default. 
defaultGovernment must
default ensure that LPAs and the Planning Inspectorate give appropriate weight to biodiversity policies, just as they do to, for example, housing policies. 
default8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLPAs need better g
defaultuidance on how to avoid and mitigate harm, and it is crucial that a single guidance document is published on every aspect of the mitigation hierarchy. This must contain very clear guidance on how to assess harm, avoid harm, mitigate harm, and finally – off
defaultse
defaultt 
defaultharm
default. 
defaultEdefaultcological expertisedefault within planning authorities default default9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe metric applied to offsetting is merely a simple articulation of what will often be a complex decision. 
defaultIt takes significant ecological expertise to be able to assess the ‘value’ of a site an
defaultd to understand how, or if, its loss can be compensated.
default Such an exercise will necessarily requi
defaultre a degree of judgement, and while it is the responsibility of the developer to provide the initial assessment, 
defaultthe LPA cannot fulfil its role as a competent d
defaultecision-maker if it is unable to verify the information. 
default10.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe world of land use planning is highly contested by a myriad of different interests, and the integrity of the planning system depends on independent arbitration. Moreover, the public’s faith in th
defaulte 
defaultsystem
default depends on independent arbitration. The decision to approve an 
defaultapplication may hinge on matters relating to biodiversity and it would be unacceptable for a LPA to have to sim
defaultply accept the developer’s recommendation on offsetting – even if the rep
defaultort is written by an ‘accredited’ expert. 
defaultAccredited or otherwise, a consultant is ultimately being paid
default by a developer
default -
default 
defaultwho will have
default a clear vested interest in obtaining planning permission.
default 
defaultWe would strongly recommend a system of accreditation but this cannot be a substitute for LPA ecological expertise. Many planning consultants are ‘accredited’ by the Royal Town Planning Institute (RTPI), but no-one would seriously suggest 
defaultthat this negates
default the need for local authority planning officers. It is equally unacceptable for LPAs not to have any ecological expertise, simply because consultants are accredited. 
default11.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOne of the potential benefits of an
default offsetting system would be
default the strategic choice of of
defaultfs
defaultet type and location, involving
default the replacement of lower value habitat with higher value habitats
default (higher value habitats should generally be replaced like for like)
default. While certain habitats are of national importance (and this needs to be reflected in any
default metric
defaults), ‘value’ will vary according to local
default ecological
default context. 
defaultEcological expertise
default is therefore needed 
defaultto ensure that local metric
defaults reflect local value, and strategic plans maximise opportunities for enhancing the local ecological network with offset
defaults. 
default12.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGiven the critical importance of local authority ecological expertise in both reducing risk and maximising potential benefits associated with offsets, it is highly alarming that less t
defaulth
defaultan 30% 
defaultof local authorities have any ecological expertise. 
defaultAll loca
defaultl authorities must have ready access to independent ecological expertise before a biodiversity offsetting system can be reliably implemented.
default 
