default. 
default14.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe share the Government’s desire for a faster and simpler planning system that brings forward the sustainable development that society needs. A faster system depends 
defaulton increased simplicity, and the system will only become simpler for all users
default,
default if all users are using the same system. It is very difficult to reconcile the Government’s contradictory desire for a 
defaultsimple system, and 
defaultfor developers to be able to opt out an
defaultd use a different system. A new method will only make the planning system simpler if everyone in the planning
default system uses it.
default15.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNor will a scheme deliver effective protection for biodiversity if a threshold is applied below which developers will not be requi
defaultred to participate. 
defaultA
default standard and explicit system for assessing potential harm to biodiversity would
default 
default only bring margin
defaultal conservation benefits if solely
default applied to major developments; whereas there would be significant benefits if
default it was
default applied to all n
defaultew housing development, new commercial buildings and to large commercial extensions. 
defaultWe recognise that direct participation in an offsetting scheme may be prohibitively expensive for some of the smallest developers—in such cases, it may be possible to impl
defaultement a form of the Community Infrastructure Levy, where businesses 
defaultwould pay a levy to the local planning authority which would then strategically offset any unavoidable damage associated with the development.
defaultMetricsdefault16.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere must be a consistent framework 
defaultfor local authorities to produce their own metrics within an offsetting supplementary planning document. This is because the value of a habitat may vary depending on context. For example, woodland may be
default extremely
default rare in an urban authority and this would 
defaultneed to be reflected in 
defaultthe ‘score’
default used
default to express its value.
default17.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere must also be national guidelines that set minimum scores for
default nationally important
default priority habitats and species
default, so that, for example, a local authority in Dorset could not set a low sco
defaultre for 
defaultnationally rare 
defaulthe
defaultathland
default,
default on the basis that it is
default not considered rare in that district. 
default18.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultS
defaultpecies should 
defaultalso 
defaultbe included in
default any future
default metric
defaults, and this needs to be accompanied by much better data on general populations, so that the value of a loca
defaultl population can be determined. Storing all data collected as part of a new standardised system, both for existing/ lost sites and for offsetting sites, could be hugely beneficial in this regard. This data should be stored nationally by Natural England, vi
defaulta LPAs. 
defaultProtectiondefault and management of offset sites default19.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFor offsetting to stand any chance of
default avoiding net losses,
default 
defaultsites must be protected and managed 
defaultover ecologically relevant timeframes. 
default20.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNatural processes require
default very l
defaultarge areas of natural land that are 
defaultseldom found in England
default. Unfortunately, this renders most habitats in need of continual management and this would be the case for most offset sites, thus making ongoing management an additional cost
default 
defaulton top of the upfront costs 
defaultassociated with creating the 
defaulthabitat
