default22.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn order to overcome the danger of either the developer or the offset provider ceasing to operate (there is a danger this 
defaultcould be premeditated) it is critically important that monies are collected prior to the commencement of development and this money is paid into a trust fund. 
defaultWe recommend
default that this trust fund is operated by one of 
defaultDefra’s
default agencies – preferably Natural 
defaultEng
defaultland. This would enable additional oversight and the ability to withhold funds if the offset provider was not meeting the conditions of their agreement. 
defaultClear responsibility and the ability to enforcedefault23.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWithout clear legal and financial arrangements in place at the outset, there is no guarantee that an offsetting provision would be reliable. 
defaultThere must be a robust legal agreement that sets out clear responsibility for the implementation and management of 
defaultan offset. 
defaultCritically, this has to enable enforcement to be taken against a specified party at any time
default,
default for the duration of the agreement. 
defaultIn particular, i
defaultt must also be possible to take punitive action against a third-party that 
defaultfails to fulfil its obligations. 
defaultAs such, it is
default inconceivable that a third-party would not be bound by a legal agreement at the planning stage, as the delivery of the offset is integral to the decision to grant planning permission. It is, therefore, alarmi
defaultng that the Green Paper suggests
default that provision of an offset by a third-party could avoid the need for detailed requirements
default regarding compensatory measures in s106 or similar agreements. You cannot grant planning permission, subject to a legal agreement,
default if the legal agreement does not secure all
default of
default the measures necessary to make the development acceptable. 
default24.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIf the granting of planning permission is dependent on satisfactory offsetting,
default there must
default also
default be a clear legal responsibility on the competent auth
defaultority to enforce the offset for the duration of the agreement, with this being the LPA in most cases. 
defaultHowever, 
defaultit may be advantageous from a conservation perspective for the offsetting to
default take
default place outside of the local authority where the development take
defaults place
default and permission is
default granted
default.
default 
defaultClarification would be
default needed 
defaultas to how enforcement action could
default be taken 
defaultin such circumstances, if, for example, a management agreement was not being adhered to. 
default25.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFurthermore, if 
defaultcommuted sums are 
defaulttaken
default by LPAs
default for small
defaulter developments (to enable cumulative funding for strategic offsetting)
default in lieu of any offset 
defaultprov
defaultision, the monies must be 
defaultring-fenced
default and used for conservation
default, and there must be a robust legal agreement in place with the subsequent offset provider
default -
default tha
defaultt 
defaultcan
default be enforced through a civil mechanism. 
defaultEnsuring defaultadditionalitydefault default26.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAny offsetting provision must be additional to any existing statutory or policy obligations. For example, this means that it would not be acceptable for aftercare from a minerals site (t
defaulthat was a conditi
defaulton of the permission) to be used to offset harm fr
defaultom another development, as the aftercare
default was necessary to offset the harm from the mineral extraction. However, the aftercare agreement would typically be time limited, and 
defaultin some circumst
defaultances 
defaultwe would be comfortable for the site to be sold as an offset once the planning obligation had expired, 
defaultif
default this would secure additional funding 
defaultnecessary 
defaultto manage the site. 
defaultLikewise, it would be unacceptable for Government to 
defaultgenerate funds needed to 
defaultfulfil its existing obligations for managing protected sites
default through offsetting
default. Neither would it be acceptable to use 
defaultagri
default-environment funded work to offset harm elsewhere, during the timeframe of the agreement. The integrity of t
defaulthe system depends on 
defaultadditionality
default and without 
defaultadditionality
default we will end up with severe net-losses of biodiversity. 
default27.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is also important to avoid offset provision being ‘double-sold’. This will require a central register, preferabl
defaulty
default maintained by Natural 
defaultEngland,
default 
defaultthat holds details of all offset provision. 
defaultMonitoringdefault28.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOne of the main benefits of introducing a standard system is that it enables effective monitoring
default and analysis
default of net changes. This means that Natural England should be requi
defaultred to collect th
defaulte data
default of the
default initial assessment of the s
defaultite, in order to understand what has been lost
default. There must also be a legal agreement as part of the planning consent that requires the submission of monitoring reports of the offset to the LPA
default. These should also be 
defaultstandardised so that the assessments of the site follows the same criteria as those used when deciding whether or not to offset. This data should in turn be submitted to Natural England. Understanding changes in the extent of different habitats will also b
defaulte necessary to inform the revisi
defaulton of criteria for valuing habitats, as value may change according to changes in extent
default.
defaultOffset type and locationdefault default29.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHigh value habitats must be protected accordingly. T
defaulthis means that permission 
defaultshould only be granted on sites
default that have a high ‘score’ in exceptional circumstances. The bar for what constitutes necessary development should rise commensurate with the score - and the likelihood of granting permission should decrease. 
defaultFurthermore, i
defaultf a high value habitat is lost, we
default would expect that habitat to be replaced like-for-like, wherever possible. 
default30.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultF
defaultor sites with lower scores 
default(
defaultespecially smaller sites
default), offsetting with a higher value habitat in a strategic location could lead to significant ecological gains. 
defaultIn order to maxi
defaultmise this potential, neighbouring LPAs should work with each other and with their Local Nature Partnerships
default, to identify strategic locations where cumulative offsetting could do most to improve ecological connectivity and deliver landscape-scale conservat
defaultion. This strategy should then be embedded in the LPAs SPD for offsetting.
default31.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultHowever, while strategically locating offsets has the potential to deliver ecological gains, distancing communities 
defaultfrom biodiversity can also incur
default a social cost.
default 
default 
defaultFor instance, t
defaultaking a small wildlife reserve from an ecologically deprived location could have a significantly negative impact on that community’s quality of life.  LPAs will need to carefully balance the needs of people and wildlife, and these trade-offs should be expl
defaulticitly addressed when 
defaultplanning for the strategic implementation of offsets. 
